The Grand Hall
A large hallway adorned with military banners and decor, with several large columns supporting the roof of the castle. There appears to be several scorch marks  around the walls and floors of the hall, along with a  gaint hole in the roof, presumably made from the dragon.
You can see a Talking door.
You can go south or north.
> speak to talking door

> speak to talking door

"Those who wanteth to passeth through mine doors, wilt first correctly answereth mine riddles. First, what is your name?"

> dave
"Dave", you answer.

"Thou art correcteth", said the Talking door.

You point out that the riddle wasn't much of a riddle and questions if the door knew what a riddle was.

"Quite mortal, I'm the door of many riddles that guards this hall and thou shall knoweth thy placeth!", exclaims the Talking door.

"Anon for mine second riddle. What hath a foot but nay legs."

> snail
"A snail", you answer.

"Correcteth again. thou is good at answering mine riddles", said the Talking door

You, again point out flaws in his riddles, claiming that his riddles are "Easy".

"EASY!", yelled the Talking door.

"Thou proclaim mine riddle's easy? the riddles that i, over a thousand years hast created and perfected!"

"Fine. if thou insist, i presenteth thou mine lasteth riddle. But be warned, this riddle is the hardest riddle that i hast devised and nay one person hath ever answered correctly. If answered incorrectly will reslut in thy death."

"Which creature walks on four legs in the morning, two legs in the afternoon, and three legs in the evening?"

> man
"A man", you answer.

"Ha! wro. . . waiteth that was correcteth. Argh!", said the Talking door.

"Okay. Anon that was just a testeth to seeth if thou wast worthy enough for mine hardest riddle."

"Anon trembleth in feareth as i presenteth thou mine hardest of hardest riddles."

"From the beginning of eternity, to the end of time and space, to the beginning of every end and the end of every place. Whateth am I?"

> e
'The letter E', you answer.

"I give up. You win, you bestest my riddles", said the Talking door while breaking his shakespearean persona.

"I should of listened to mum and stayed as doggy door", muttered the Talking door as he slowy opens to reveal the next area.

